const a = [
  {"id":7092,"text":"Which one of the following represents the female pelvis with a greater transverse diameter of the outlet than the anteroposterior diameter?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 561.","responses":[{"text":"Platypelloid pelvis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesatipellic pelvis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dolicocephalic pelvis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gynecoid pelvis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Android pelvis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7189,"text":"A 15-year-old girl comes to the outpatient department with complaints of cyclical lower abdominal pain. On examination, she has suprapubic swelling and a bluish bulge is seen in the vestibule. What is the most probable cause?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 274.","responses":[{"text":"Congenital adrenal hyperplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"XY gonadal genesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Turner syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mullerian agenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Imperforate hymen","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7193,"text":"Which is the most common site of implantation of the fetus in an ectopic pregnancy?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1029.","responses":[{"text":"Cervix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Isthmus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uterus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ampulla","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Infundibulum","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7207,"text":"A 30-year-old female patient is being evaluated for infertility. Serum gonadotropins, estradiol, progesterone, and prolactin levels are measured in a test that is advised to obtain data by a blood sample on her 21st day of menstruation cycle. Which of the following will indicate if the cycle has been ovulatory or not?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1031, 1037.","responses":[{"text":"Estradiol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leutinizing hormone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7342,"text":"Which of the following lymph nodes do testes drain into?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 432.","responses":[{"text":"Superficial inguinal lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Deep inguinal lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Para-aortic lymph nodes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Femoral lymph nodes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7430,"text":"A 22-year-old medical student presents to the clinic with a history of weight gain, worsening and thickened facial hair, and irregular periods. What could she possibly be suffering from?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1016.","responses":[{"text":"Endometrial cancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uterine fibroids","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical dysplasia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pelvic pain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS)","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":9360,"text":"Which of the following is the rate-limiting enzyme in cholesterol synthesis?","explanation":null,"reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 221.","responses":[{"text":"Prenyl transferase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squalene synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HMG-CoA reductase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"HMG-CoA synthase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mevalonate carboxylase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9560,"text":"Ovaries of a young girl who has not yet reached puberty contain which of the following structures?","explanation":"**Before puberty**, the **ovaries** contain primordial follicles. These primordial follicles consist of an oocyte surrounded by a single layer of squamous follicular cells. As a girl approaches puberty, some of these **primordial follicles** will start to undergo development, progressing to primary and then secondary follicles.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPrimary follicles are follicles that have begun to develop but have not yet reached the stage of ovulation.\r\n\r\nSecondary follicles are follicles that have developed further than primary follicles and have begun to produce estrogen.\r\n\r\nSecondary oocytes are released from the ovary during ovulation after the onset of puberty.\r\n\r\nAtretic follicles are follicles that have stopped developing and will eventually die. They are not the predominant type of follicle in prepubertal ovaries.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., T. V. N. Persaud, and Mark G. Torchia. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2016: 17.","responses":[{"text":"Primordial follicles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary follicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atretic follicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary follicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Secondary oocyte","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9646,"text":"As menstruation ends, estrogen levels in the blood rise rapidly. What is the source of estrogen?","explanation":"As menstruation ends, the rising estrogen levels in the blood are primarily attributed to the **developing follicles** in the ovaries. The follicles, which contain the developing oocytes (eggs), **produce estrogen** during the follicular phase of the menstrual cycle.\r\n\r\nThe **granulosa cells** within the ovarian follicles are responsible for synthesizing and releasing estrogen, particularly estradiol. This estrogen production is essential for the preparation of the endometrium (lining of the uterus) for the possibility of pregnancy.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAlthough the corpus luteum also secretes estrogen, it is formed during the latter half of the menstrual cycle, after ovulation has occurred. In contrast, the initial rise in estrogen occurs during the early phase of the menstrual cycle, which precedes the formation of the corpus luteum.\r\n\r\nWhile the stromal cells are part of the ovarian structure, they are not the primary source of estrogen. Estrogen is mainly produced by the granulosa cells within the developing ovarian follicles.\r\n\r\nThe endometrium is the inner lining of the uterus, and while it is influenced by estrogen, it is not the primary source of estrogen production.\r\n\r\nThe anterior pituitary gland secretes hormones that regulate ovarian function but it is not a direct source of estrogen.","reference":"Thiyagarajan DK, Basit H, Jeanmonod R. Physiology, menstrual cycle. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed December 12, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK500020/","responses":[{"text":"Corpus luteum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Developing follicles","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Endometrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior pituitary gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stromal cells of ovaries","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9647,"text":"Which of the following enzymes is required to convert testosterone to estradiol?","explanation":"**Aromatase** is a cytochrome P450 enzyme that plays a crucial role in the biosynthesis of estrogen. It catalyzes the **conversion** of androgens such as **testosterone** into estrogens such as **estradiol** by aromatization.\r\n\r\nDuring this process, the aromatase enzyme facilitates the removal of the methyl group from the C-19 position of androgens, leading to the formation of estrogens. This conversion is significant in various physiological processes, including the regulation of reproductive and sexual development.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nLyases are involved in breaking chemical bonds but are not specifically associated with the conversion of testosterone to estradiol.\r\n\r\nOxygenase enzymes incorporate oxygen into substrates, but they are not responsible for the conversion of testosterone to estradiol.\r\n\r\nIsomerase enzymes catalyze the conversion of one isomer to another, but they are not involved in the conversion of testosterone to estradiol.\r\n\r\nDehydrogenase enzymes catalyze the removal of hydrogen atoms but are not specifically involved in the conversion of testosterone to estradiol.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1032.","responses":[{"text":"Isomerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygenase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aromatase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lyase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dehydrogenase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12849,"text":"Which of the following is another name for the suspensory ligament of the ovary?","explanation":"The **suspensory ligament of the ovary** is a peritoneal fold that is also known as the **infundibulopelvic ligament**. The term \"infundibulopelvic\" reflects its anatomical course as it extends from the ovaries near the infundibulum of the fallopian tubes and passes down (inferiorly) to the pelvic wall, playing a crucial role in supporting the ovary within the pelvic cavity. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe utero-ovarian ligament, which connects the uterus to the ovary, is separate from the suspensory ligament.\r\n\r\nThe uterosacral ligament connects the uterus to the sacrum, not the ovary.\r\n\r\nThe pubocervical ligament connects the pubic bone to the cervix, not the ovary.\r\n\r\nNo widely recognized ligament named transverse ovarian ligament exists in the context of ovarian support.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 477.","responses":[{"text":"Transverse ovarian ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Utero-ovarian ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pubocervical ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infundibulopelvic ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Uterosacral ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12850,"text":"Perineal spaces are divided into superficial and deep by means of which of the following structures?","explanation":"The **perineal membrane** is a dense, fibrous sheet that is formed by the inferior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm. It creates a clear **division** between the superficial and deep **perineal spaces** (pouches), with the superficial pouch lying inferiorly and the deep pouch lying superiorly.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe skin is the outermost layer of the body and doesn't play a role in dividing the perineal spaces.\r\n\r\nColles' fascia refers to the membranous layer of the superficial perineal fascia. \r\n\r\nThe urogenital diaphragm is a muscular layer that forms the floor of the pelvis and contributes to the deep perineal space.\r\n\r\nPerineal pouches are potential spaces that are formed by the division of the perineal space. The superficial perineal pouch is enclosed by the Colles fascia inferiorly and the perineal membrane superiorly.\r\n\r\nThe deep perineal pouch lies above the perineal membrane. Superiorly, the deep perineal pouch is bound by the superior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 496, 500.","responses":[{"text":"Perineal pouch","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Colles' fascia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Skin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Perineal membrane","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Urogenital diaphragm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12851,"text":"The navicular fossa is present in which of the following structures?","explanation":"The **navicular fossa**, also known as the fossa navicularis, is one of two dilations found in the **penile urethra**. It is located in the glans penis near the **terminal end** of the penile urethra, just before the external urethral orifice. This anatomical feature is important in terms of clinical examinations and procedures involving the male urethra.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe dilation of the initial part of the penile urethra forms the intrabulbar fossa as it passes through the bulb of the penis.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 461.","responses":[{"text":"Initial part of penile urethra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Membranous urethra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal part of penile urethra","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostatic urethra","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intramural part of urethra","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12852,"text":"Choose the correct order for the path of sperm from the testes to outside the body.","explanation":"The correct order for the path of sperm from the testes to outside the body is given below.\r\n\r\n1. **Epididymis:** It is a convoluted duct where sperm mature and gain the ability to swim. It is continuous with the ductus deferens.\r\n2. **Ductus deferens:** After exiting the epididymis, sperm travel through the ductus deferens - a muscular tube that propels them toward the ejaculatory duct.\r\n3. **Ejaculatory duct:** The ductus deferens merges with the seminal vesicle to form the ejaculatory duct, which then empties into the urethra.\r\n4. **Penis:** Finally, during ejaculation, sperm and seminal fluids exit the body through the penis.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 595, 596, 604.","responses":[{"text":"Ejaculatory duct -\u003e ductus deferens -\u003e epididymis -\u003e penis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Penis -\u003e ductus deferens -\u003e epididymis -\u003e ejaculatory duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ductus deferens -\u003e ejaculatory duct -\u003e epididymis -\u003e penis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ductus deferens -\u003e epididymis -\u003e ejaculatory duct -\u003e penis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epididymis -\u003e ductus deferens -\u003e ejaculatory duct -\u003e penis","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12853,"text":"An infertile couple comes into the infertility clinic to seek advice because the X-ray report of the uterine tube (hysterosalpingography) reveals a blockage in part of the tube that opens into the peritoneal cavity. What is the blocked part of the tube?","explanation":"The blocked part of the uterine tube in this case is the **infundibulum**, which is the most distal portion of the tube, **opening** directly into the **peritoneal cavity**.\r\n\r\nThe infundibulum is the funnel-shaped opening of the uterine tube that surrounds the ovary. It is responsible for capturing the released egg (ovum) from the ovary. Any blockage in the infundibulum can impede the passage of the egg into the tube and hinder its journey toward potential fertilization.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe ampulla is the widest part of the uterine tube, located between the infundibulum and the isthmus.\r\n\r\nThe isthmus is the narrow portion of the tube that connects the uterus to the ampulla.\r\n\r\nThe intramural or interstitial part of the uterine tube passes through the uterine wall.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 472.","responses":[{"text":"Interstitial","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infundibulum","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Isthmus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ampulla","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intramural","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12854,"text":"A postgraduate 1st year resident of gynecology and obstetrics was discussing with undergraduate students during the morning round about normal menstrual cycle and menstrual irregularities. Which of the following represents the correct order of events during the menstrual cycle?","explanation":"The correct sequence of events during the menstrual cycle is given below.\r\n\r\n1. **Menstruation:** The cycle begins with the shedding of the uterine lining (endometrium) in response to the previous cycle's drop in hormone levels.\r\n\r\n2. **Follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) rise:** Following menstruation, there is a rise in FSH, which stimulates the development of ovarian follicles.\r\n\r\n3. **Luteinizing hormone (LH) surge:** As the dominant follicle matures, it releases increasing amounts of estrogen, leading to a surge in LH, which triggers ovulation.\r\n\r\n4. **Ovulation:** The mature follicle ruptures, releasing an egg (ovum) from the ovary into the fallopian tube, making it available for fertilization.\r\n\r\n5. **Luteal phase:** After ovulation, the ruptured follicle transforms into the corpus luteum, producing progesterone and preparing the endometrium for a potential pregnancy.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1036.","responses":[{"text":"FSH rise, ovulation, LH surge, luteal phase, menstruation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular phase, luteal phase, FSH rise, ovulation, menstruation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteal phase, menstruation, FSH rise, ovulation, follicular phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FSH rise, menstruation, LH surge, luteal Phase, ovulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Menstruation, FSH rise, LH surge, ovulation, luteal phase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12891,"text":"To decrease surface tension and open the lungs during birth, significant negative intrapleural pressure is required for the first breath. How much is this pressure?","explanation":"Significant **negative intrapleural pressure** is required during birth to decrease surface tension and open the lungs for the **first breath**. The correct amount of this negative pressure is more than 25 mmHg, with the first neonatal breath being able to produce a pressure of approximately **-60 mmHg**.\r\n\r\nNegative intrapleural pressure is crucial in expanding the lungs by opposing the natural tendency of the lungs to collapse due to surface tension. This negative pressure is created by the contraction of the diaphragm and the expansion of the thoracic cavity during the inspiratory phase of the first breath.\r\n\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAn intrapleural pressure of less than -25 mmHg is not sufficient to overcome surface tension and open the lungs effectively.\r\n\r\n-100 mmHg is excessively negative and not physiologically accurate for the intrapleural pressure required during the first breath.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1063.","responses":[{"text":"-5 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"-2 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"-15 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"-60 mmHg","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"-100 mmHg","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12894,"text":"The luteal phase of the ovarian cycle corresponds to which phase of the uterine cycle?","explanation":"The **luteal phase of the ovarian cycle** aligns with the **secretory phase of the uterine cycle** because both involve progesterone dominance and preparation of the endometrium for a potential pregnancy.\r\n\r\n**Ovarian cycle**\r\n\r\n- Follicular phase: This phase begins with the development of a dominant ovarian follicle, culminating in ovulation.\r\n- Ovulatory phase: Ovulation results in the release of the egg from the ovary.\r\n- **Luteal phase:** After ovulation, the ruptured follicle transforms into the corpus luteum, producing progesterone.\r\n\r\n**Uterine cycle**\r\n\r\n- Menstrual phase: Shedding of the uterine lining occurs if there is no pregnancy.\r\n- Proliferative phase: The endometrium rebuilds and thickens in response to increasing estrogen levels from the developing ovarian follicles.\r\n- **Secretory phase:** If fertilization occurs, the corpus luteum secretes progesterone, leading to increased vascularity and glandular development in the endometrium.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe menstrual phase of the uterine cycle corresponds to the shedding of the uterine lining and is not the counterpart to the luteal phase.\r\n\r\nThe proliferative phase of the uterine cycle corresponds to the follicular phase of the ovarian cycle.\r\n\r\nThe follicular and ovulatory phases precede the luteal phase of the ovarian cycle.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1032, 1037.","responses":[{"text":"Secretory phase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proliferative phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Menstrual phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovulatory phase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12895,"text":"Which of the following is the major trophic hormone for Sertoli cells and the major stimulator for aromatase activity of Sertoli cells?","explanation":"The **follicle-stimulating hormone** (FSH) plays a major role in spermatogenesis. It acts as a trophic hormone for **Sertoli cells** in the testes, stimulating their **growth** and development.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, FSH is the major stimulator for **aromatase** activity in Sertoli cells. Aromatase is an enzyme that converts testosterone into **estradiol** (estrogen), which is essential for the proper regulation of spermatogenesis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nMelatonin is a hormone produced by the pineal gland that regulates sleep-wake cycles. It is not directly involved in the regulation of Sertoli cells.\r\n\r\nInhibin is produced by Sertoli cells and plays a role in negative feedback regulation by inhibiting FSH secretion.\r\n\r\nLuteinizing hormone (LH) primarily acts on Leydig cells to stimulate testosterone production and is not the major trophic hormone for Sertoli cells.\r\n\r\nTestosterone is produced by Leydig cells in the testes. While it is essential for the development and function of male reproductive organs, testosterone is not the major trophic hormone for Sertoli cells.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1018, 1033.","responses":[{"text":"Melatonin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"LH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FSH","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12897,"text":"Testicular feminization syndrome is caused by a mutation in genes coding for which of the following?","explanation":"**Testicular feminization syndrome** is also known as androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS). It is caused by a mutation in the **androgen receptor gene** located on the **X chromosome**. This mutation affects the function of the androgen receptor, making the target tissues insensitive to androgens, including testosterone and dihydrotestosterone (DHT).\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAndrogen-binding protein is involved in the transport of testosterone in the male reproductive system but is not directly associated with testicular feminization syndrome.\r\n\r\nTestosterone 5-alpha reductase is responsible for converting testosterone into its more potent form, dihydrotestosterone (DHT). Mutations in this enzyme are associated with 5-alpha-reductase deficiency but not testicular feminization syndrome.\r\n\r\nWhile estrogen receptors play a role in mediating the effects of estrogen in the body, mutations in estrogen receptors are not associated with testicular feminization syndrome.\r\n\r\nInhibin is a hormone produced by Sertoli cells in the testes and has a role in feedback regulation of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) secretion. It is not directly related to the androgen insensitivity observed in testicular feminization syndrome.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 272.","responses":[{"text":"Estrogen receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Androgen receptor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Androgen-binding protein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testosterone 5-alpha reductase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12902,"text":"At which site is the testis-determining gene (or the SRY gene) located normally?","explanation":"The **sex-determining region Y (SRY) gene** is a critical gene located on the short arm of the **Y chromosome**. It plays a central role in determining the development of male characteristics during embryogenesis and is also known as the testis-determining gene.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nChromosome 6 is known for hosting the major histocompatibility complex (MHC) genes, which play a crucial role in the immune system.\r\n\r\nThe short arm of chromosome 22 is associated with genetic disorders such as DiGeorge syndrome but is not related to sex determination. \r\n\r\nChromosome 12 contains genes involved in various biological processes. For instance, it carries genes related to blood clotting factors.\r\n\r\nChromosome 8 contains genes associated with conditions such as breast cancer.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 261.","responses":[{"text":"Y chromosome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Short arm of chromosome 22","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromosome 8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromosome 12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chromosome 6","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12903,"text":"A 4-year-old girl presents with bilateral inguinal masses, thought to be hernias, but these are found to be testes in the inguinal canals. Which of the following is most likely the karyotype?","explanation":"The presence of bilateral undescended testes in a 4-year-old girl is indicative of **androgen insensitivity syndrome** (AIS). AIS is a condition where there is **defective** androgen **receptor** function, leading to a lack of response to androgens such as testosterone. The individual with AIS is **genetically male** (**46 XY**) but externally appears female due to the inability of androgens to masculinize the external genitalia.\r\n\r\nIn AIS, the affected individual has a 46 XY karyotype but presents **phenotypically** as **female**. This is because the testes produce anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) leading to regression of Müllerian structures, but the lack of androgen receptor function **prevents** the **development of male external genitalia**.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe 45 XY karyotype does not reflect the typical male karyotype.\r\n\r\nThe 47 XXY karyotype is associated with Klinefelter syndrome. It is characterized by male hypogonadism and is not associated with ambiguous genitalia.\r\n\r\nThe 47 XYY karyotype is associated with tall stature and learning disabilities, not ambiguous genitalia.\r\n\r\n46 XX is the typical female karyotype and is not consistent with the presence of testes in the inguinal canals.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 272.","responses":[{"text":"45 XY","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"47 XYY","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"46 XX","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"47 XXY","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"46 XY","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12904,"text":"Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) acts upon which of the following receptors?","explanation":"**Human chorionic gonadotropin** (hCG) acts upon the **luteinizing hormone** (LH) **receptor**. This is because hCG and LH share a common alpha subunit and similar molecular weight (approximately 39,000), allowing hCG to bind to and activate the LH receptor.\r\n\r\nHuman chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) is a glycoprotein hormone produced by the syncytiotrophoblast cells of the placenta during pregnancy. It plays a crucial role in maintaining the corpus luteum, which, in turn, produces progesterone during early pregnancy.\r\n\r\nThe LH receptor is primarily located in the gonads, specifically in the Leydig cells of the testes in males and the granulosa and theca cells of the ovaries in females. Activation of the LH receptor by hCG in a male fetus stimulates the production of testosterone\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHuman placental lactogen (human chorionic somatomammotropin) acts on its specific receptors and is involved in promoting mammary gland development and regulating maternal glucose and fat metabolism during pregnancy. \r\n\r\nProlactin acts on the prolactin hormone receptor receptor to stimulate milk production in mammary glands.\r\n\r\nGrowth hormone (GH) acts on the growth hormone receptor to promote growth and metabolism.\r\n\r\nThe follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) acts on the FSH receptor to regulate the development and maturation of ovarian follicles in females and spermatogenesis in males.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1049.","responses":[{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin hormone receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human placental lactogen receptor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone receptor","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone receptor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12906,"text":"Theca interna cells have an important function in ovarian follicle development. Which of the following organelles is abundant in these cells because of this function?","explanation":"**Theca interna cells** play a crucial role in the development and maturation of ovarian follicles. One of their significant functions is the production of sex hormones, primarily androgens, which are precursors for the synthesis of estrogen.\r\n\r\nThe **smooth endoplasmic reticulum** (SER) is a membrane-bound cellular organelle involved in **lipid synthesis** and metabolism. In the context of theca interna cells, the abundance of smooth endoplasmic reticulum is related to the synthesis of **androgens**, particularly testosterone. These androgens are then transported to granulosa cells, where they are converted into estrogen, contributing to the overall hormonal milieu necessary for ovarian follicle development.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nPolyribosomes are clusters of ribosomes involved in protein synthesis.\r\n\r\nLysosomes are not directly involved in the synthesis of sex hormones. They are primarily responsible for the breakdown of cellular waste and recycling of cellular components.\r\n\r\nGolgi apparatus is not specifically known for its role in androgen synthesis. It is involved in processing and packaging proteins for secretion or use within the cell.\r\n\r\nCentrioles are involved in cell division and organization of the cytoskeleton.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 234.","responses":[{"text":"Golgi apparatus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lysosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Centrioles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyribosomes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth endoplasmic reticulum","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12918,"text":"A histologist while observing the slide of a reproductive organ observes primordial follicles at various stages of development at the periphery. The central region contains blood vessels in loose connective tissue. The organ is most likely which of the following?","explanation":"**Primordial follicles** are the earliest stage of ovarian follicle development and consist of an immature egg (oocyte) surrounded by a single layer of flattened granulosa cells. These structures are typically found at the **periphery** of the **ovary**. As follicles develop, they progress through stages such as primary and secondary follicles, eventually maturing into Graafian follicles.\r\n\r\nThe **central region** containing blood vessels in loose connective tissue is consistent with the **ovarian stroma**, which supports the follicular structures.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe cervix is primarily composed of connective tissue and smooth muscle and does not exhibit the characteristic follicular structures found in the ovary.\r\n\r\nThe uterus contains layers of smooth muscle and is not the site of primordial follicle development.\r\n\r\nThe vagina is a muscular tube that is not involved in ovarian follicle development.\r\n\r\nWhile the fallopian tubes play a crucial role in transporting eggs from the ovaries to the uterus, they do not typically contain primordial follicles.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 231.","responses":[{"text":"Cervix","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Uterus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovary","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Fallopian tube","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagina","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12919,"text":"The hallmark histological feature of the prostate is the fibromuscular stroma in which there are clusters of smooth muscles mixed with elastic fibers. What is the most commonly seen type of epithelium in the prostate?","explanation":"The **prostate** is a glandular organ that surrounds the urethra in males. The glandular tissue of the prostate is composed of tubuloalveolar glands, and the **epithelium** lining these glands is **predominantly simple columnar**. This type of epithelium is well-suited for **glandular secretion**.\r\n\r\nThe **fibromuscular stroma** of the prostate consists of bundles of smooth muscles interspersed with elastic fibers. This stromal tissue provides structural support to the glandular elements of the prostate.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTransitional epithelium is commonly found in areas that undergo stretching and relaxation, such as the urinary bladder.\r\n\r\nWhile simple cuboidal epithelium may be present in some regions of the prostate, the predominant type of epithelium is simple columnar.\r\n\r\nSimple squamous epithelium is typically found in areas where thin and permeable membranes are needed, such as the alveoli of the lungs.\r\n\r\nThe stratified squamous epithelium is more characteristic of structures such as the epidermis of the skin.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 226.","responses":[{"text":"Simple cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transitional","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple columnar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12921,"text":"Which type of epithelial transition is seen between the vagina and cervix?","explanation":"The epithelial lining of the **vagina** is primarily composed of **stratified squamous** (nonkeratinized) epithelium. This type of epithelium is well-suited to withstand friction and stretching, protecting the vaginal canal.\r\n\r\nThe **cervix** is characterized by a transformation from stratified squamous epithelium in the vagina to **simple columnar epithelium** in the endocervical canal. This transitional region is known as the **transformation zone**.\r\n\r\nThe reason for this transition is related to the different functions of the vagina and cervix. The stratified squamous epithelium in the vagina provides protection, while the simple columnar epithelium in the cervix is involved in mucous secretion and is more conducive to the transport of sperm.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 239.","responses":[{"text":"Stratified squamous to stratified columnar epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous to simple columnar epithelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple squamous to stratified columnar epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple squamous to simple columnar epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple columnar to simple squamous epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12923,"text":"Choose the correct statement regarding the development of the vagina.","explanation":"In early embryonic development, the **paramesonephric ducts**, which are paired ducts present in the embryo, fuse in the midline. This fusion process occurs to form a single structure known as the uterovaginal canal. The upper part of the uterovaginal canal gives rise to the **upper one-third of the vagina**. This segment of the vagina is derived from the paramesonephric ducts and contributes to the formation of the female reproductive tract.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe lower part of the uterovaginal canal interacts with the sinovaginal bulb, which is an outgrowth of the urogenital sinus. The sinovaginal bulb gives rise to the lower two-thirds of the vagina.\r\n\r\nThe vaginal fornices are recesses around the cervix and are derived from the müllerian duct, not the urogenital sinus.\r\n\r\nThe hymen is a membrane that surrounds or partially covers the external vaginal opening, and it is derived from the urogenital sinus, not the müllerian duct.\r\n\r\nThe surface ectoderm forms the external genitalia such as the labia majora and minora, not the internal structures such as the vagina.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 264.","responses":[{"text":"Hymen develop from cells derived from mullerian duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagina upper two-third develops from urogenital sinus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vaginal fornices are of urogenital sinus origin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lower two-third is from surface ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper one-third from fused paramesonephric duct","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12924,"text":"Patients with androgen insensitivity syndrome (AIS) are normal-appearing females with 46 XY chromosome patterns. Internal genitalia of such patients includes which of the following?","explanation":"**Androgen insensitivity syndrome** (AIS) is a genetic condition characterized by a **46 XY** chromosome pattern with a defect in the androgen receptor, leading to a lack of response to androgens such as testosterone. Despite having a male chromosomal pattern, individuals with AIS develop external genitalia that appear typically female.\r\n\r\n**Internally**, individuals with AIS have structures that are consistent with **male development**. This includes the presence of **testes**, which may be located in the inguinal canals or within the abdominal cavity. However, there is an absence or underdevelopment of male reproductive structures such as the prostate and seminal vesicles.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe internal structures in individuals with AIS are consistent with male development despite the external appearance being female. The uterus, fallopian tubes, and ovaries are typically absent or severely underdeveloped.\r\n\r\nThe prostate is a male reproductive organ and is not typically present or well-developed in individuals with AIS.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 272.","responses":[{"text":"Uterus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fallopian tube","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testes","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12925,"text":"Regarding external genitals in the female, which of the following structures develop from genital swelling?","explanation":"During the early stages of embryonic development, the genital tubercle and the urogenital folds contribute to the formation of the external genitalia.\r\n\r\nThe **genital swelling**, which is a part of this process, gives rise to the **labia majora**. These are the prominent, outer folds of skin that enclose and protect the other structures of the external female genitalia.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe clitoris is derived from the genital tubercle.\r\n\r\nThe labia minora are derived from the urogenital folds.\r\n\r\nThe vaginal orifice arises from the fusion of separate structures called urogenital folds that flank the urogenital sinus.\r\n\r\nWhile the vestibule forms due to the fusion of genital swellings, it encompasses the vaginal orifice, making it more of a consequence than a direct derivative.","reference":"Sadler TW, Langman J. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 12th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2011: 251.","responses":[{"text":"Vaginal orifice","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clitoris","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The vestibule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Labia majora","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Labia minora","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12926,"text":"Seminal vesicles are glands of the male reproductive system located at the posterior surface of the bladder. Which of the following germ layers gives rise to seminal vesicles?","explanation":"During embryonic development, the urogenital system, including the **seminal vesicles**, originates from the **intermediate mesoderm**. The seminal vesicles are paired glands crucial for reproductive function, located at the posterior surface of the bladder.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe lateral plate mesoderm contributes to the formation of various structures including the limbs and mesenteries.\r\n\r\nThe ectoderm gives rise to the outermost layer of the embryo and is not related to the development of internal reproductive glands.\r\n\r\nThe paraxial mesoderm is associated with the development of somites and axial structures.\r\n\r\nThe endoderm forms the innermost layer and contributes to the lining of internal organs.","reference":"Sadler TW, Langman J. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 12th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2011: 232, 248.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral plate mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intermediate mesoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraxial mesoderm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectoderm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12929,"text":"Estrogen is required for normal reproductive function in the male. Which of the following is the principal site of estrogen synthesis in males?","explanation":null,"reference":"(1) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1019.\r\n\r\n(2) Chaurasia BD, Garg K, CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors Private Limited. BD Chaurasia’s Handbook of General Anatomy. 5th ed. CBS Publishers \u0026 Distributors Pvt Ltd; 2015: 601.","responses":[{"text":"Osteoblasts","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trophoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leydig cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostate cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Liver cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12930,"text":"Birth control pills containing combinations of synthetic estrogen and progesterone compounds given for the first 21 days of the menstrual cycle are effective in preventing pregnancy. What is the explanation for their efficacy?","explanation":"The efficacy of birth control pills containing **combinations of** synthetic **estrogen** and **progesterone** compounds in preventing pregnancy is primarily attributed to their influence on the female reproductive cycle. These contraceptives act by **preventing** the **preovulatory surge** of luteinizing hormone (**LH**).\r\n\r\nThe surge in LH typically triggers ovulation i.e., the release of a mature egg from the ovarian follicle. By preventing this surge, birth control pills help avert the release of an egg, thereby reducing the chances of fertilization.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe corpus luteum is formed after ovulation and is responsible for progesterone production. Birth control pills do not target the corpus luteum immediately after its formation.\r\n\r\nWhile changes in the endometrium occur with these pills, their primary mechanism of birth control is not the prevention of normal endometrial development but rather inhibiting ovulation.\r\n\r\nGonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) is not directly suppressed by these contraceptives. They act at different levels in the reproductive axis.\r\n\r\nBirth control pills do not prevent the development of ovarian follicles; rather, they primarily inhibit the surge of LH, which is crucial for ovulation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1042.","responses":[{"text":"Prevention of development of the ovarian follicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suppressing function of the corpus luteum soon after it forms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suppressing the function of GnRH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevention of normal development of the endometrium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prevention of preovulatory surge of LH","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12931,"text":"After ovulation, which female hormone stimulates the increase in the thickness of the endometrium?","explanation":"**Following ovulation**, the ruptured follicle transforms into the corpus luteum, which produces progesterone. **Progesterone** plays a crucial role in preparing the **endometrium** for potential implantation by promoting its **growth** and vascularization. This hormone supports the maintenance of the uterine lining, creating a favorable environment for implantation.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nFollicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) is involved in the development of follicles during the early phase of the menstrual cycle, but it does not play a significant role in thickening the endometrium after ovulation.\r\n\r\nLuteinizing hormone (LH) triggers ovulation but is not directly involved in thickening the endometrium post-ovulation.\r\n\r\nWhile estradiol contributes to the proliferation of the endometrium during the follicular phase, its levels decline after ovulation and it is not the primary hormone responsible for thickening the endometrium in the post-ovulatory phase.\r\n\r\nEstriol is a weak estrogen and is not the main hormone responsible for thickening the endometrium after ovulation. It is more prominent during pregnancy.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1037.","responses":[{"text":"Progesterone","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Estriol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle-stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estradiol","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12934,"text":"A 28-year-old married female visits the obstetrics outpatient department with a history of a missed period and complains of dark brown bleeding from the vagina along with severe nausea and vomiting. She also complains of the passing of grapelike cysts from the vagina. Her ultrasound finding shows the presence of many small cysts in the uterine cavity. Excessively high levels of which hormone helps in the diagnosis of this condition?","explanation":"Dark brown vaginal bleeding, severe nausea, vomiting, and the passage of grape-like cysts from the vagina are indicative of a molar pregnancy. More specifically, a **complete hydatidiform mole**. In molar pregnancies, **human chorionic gonadotropin** (hCG) levels are **excessively high** compared to a normal pregnancy, aiding in the diagnosis of this condition.\r\n\r\nIn a complete hydatidiform mole, there is abnormal fertilization of an egg without a nucleus, leading to excessive trophoblastic proliferation and cyst formation. These **cysts** appear as **grape-like structures**. The trophoblastic tissue produces markedly elevated levels of hCG - a hormone normally secreted by the placenta during pregnancy.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHuman somatomammotropin hormone (also known as human growth hormone) is not directly associated with molar pregnancies. Elevated levels of hCG are more specific to this condition.\r\n\r\nWhile estrogen levels are altered in molar pregnancies, they are not excessively high to the extent that hCG is. HCG is a more reliable marker for the diagnosis of complete hydatidiform moles.\r\n\r\nProgesterone levels are generally elevated during pregnancy but are not as specific or sensitive as hCG in diagnosing molar pregnancies.\r\n\r\nGonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) is not directly related to the diagnosis of molar pregnancies.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1034.","responses":[{"text":"Human somatomammotropin hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human chorionic gonadotropin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"GnRH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12936,"text":"A 14-year-old girl began menstruation 1 year ago. She now has irregular menstrual cycles with oligomenorrhea and amenorrhea. On examination, she has acne and increase hair growth on her face. She has an elevated ratio of LH to FSH. Which of the following is most likely to produce these findings?","explanation":"An **elevated** ratio of luteinizing hormone to follicle-stimulating hormone (**LH to FSH ratio**) in a 14-year-old girl is indicative of **polycystic ovarian syndrome** (PCOS). Patients with PCOS typically present with the following clinical features:\r\n\r\n1) Irregular menstrual cycles\r\n2) Oligomenorrhea\r\n3) Amenorrhea\r\n4) Acne\r\n5) Hirsutism\r\n\r\nPCOS is a common endocrine disorder in women of reproductive age. In this condition, there is an imbalance in the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis, leading to an increase in luteinizing hormone (LH) secretion compared to follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH). This altered ratio contributes to anovulation, irregular menstrual cycles, and the development of ovarian cysts.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nEndometrial polyps are growths in the inner lining of the uterus and are unlikely to cause anovulatory cycles and hormonal imbalances leading to an elevated LH to FSH ratio. They are more commonly associated with abnormal uterine bleeding.\r\n\r\nWhile anovulation is a characteristic feature of PCOS, anovulatory cycles alone do not fully explain the hormonal imbalance and other manifestations seen in this case.\r\n\r\nEndometrial carcinoma typically presents with abnormal uterine bleeding in postmenopausal women and is not a common cause of irregular menstrual cycles in a 14-year-old girl.\r\n\r\nEctopic pregnancy is associated with abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and a positive pregnancy test. It does not explain the hormonal imbalance and symptoms observed in this case.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2018: 144.","responses":[{"text":"Endometrial polyp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectopic pregnancy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycystic ovarian syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anovulatory cycles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endometrial carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12938,"text":"Which of the following proteins are required for the transport of estrogen in the plasma?","explanation":"The **transport of estrogen** in the plasma involves specific binding proteins, and **sex hormone binding globulin** (SHBG) is the key protein required for this function. SHBG is a glycoprotein that binds to sex hormones, including estrogen, in the bloodstream. It regulates the bioavailability and transport of these hormones, facilitating their circulation and delivery to target tissues.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nIron-binding blood protein ferritin is primarily involved in the storage of iron and is not associated with the transport of estrogen in the plasma.\r\n\r\nCorticosteroid-binding globulin binds corticosteroids, not sex hormones such as estrogen. \r\n\r\nCholesterol-binding lipoproteins such as HDL and LDL are involved in transporting cholesterol, but they do not play a significant role in the transport of estrogen.\r\n\r\nAlbumin can bind to various hormones, including estrogen. However, there is no subtype of albumin specific to the binding of sex hormones.","reference":"(1) Dow Lecture Slides. Reproductive Module. Subject: Biochemistry, Topic: Female Reproductive System, Estrogen, Sub-topic: Plasma Levels.\r\n(2) Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1034.","responses":[{"text":"Corticosteroid-binding globulin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cholesterol binding lipoproteins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iron-binding blood protein ferritin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sex hormone binding globulin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sex hormone binding albumin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12955,"text":"A 27-year-old lady undergoes uterine curettage after a spontaneous abortion. Microscopy shows intimately admixed cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast. Abundant hemorrhage and necrosis are present. No chorionic villi are seen. Radio-imaging shows nodules in both lungs as well as the brain. Which of the following statements regarding this patient's diagnosis is true?","explanation":"The described histological features of intimately admixed cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast, along with the presence of abundant hemorrhage and necrosis without chorionic villi, point towards a diagnosis of choriocarcinoma.\r\n\r\n**Gestational choriocarcinoma** is a highly malignant trophoblastic tumor that often arises following a molar pregnancy or a spontaneous abortion. It has a propensity for early hematogenous spread, and in this case, the presence of lung and brain nodules indicates metastasis. Fortunately, gestational choriocarcinoma is **highly responsive** to **chemotherapy**, making the prognosis generally favorable with timely intervention.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nChoriocarcinomas are more commonly associated with molar pregnancies than ectopic pregnancies.\r\n\r\nOvarian choriocarcinoma generally has a relatively poor prognosis, often resulting in death.\r\n\r\nIn males, choriocarcinoma is classified as a germ cell tumor, not a sex-cord stromal tumor.\r\n\r\nAlpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is associated with yolk sac tumors. In choriocarcinoma, human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) is the key tumor marker.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1025, 1035.","responses":[{"text":"Alpha-fetoprotein levels are used to monitor this disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"More than half of these tumors arise in ectopic pregnancies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovarian variant of this tumor has a very good prognosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Response to evacuation and chemotherapy is usually excellent","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"In males this tumor is classified as a sex-cord stromal tumor","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12956,"text":"A male child is brought to the pediatrician's clinic for abdominal pain. He also has vomiting and diarrhea. A detailed stool report shows infective diarrhea which responds well to antibiotics. However, his ultrasonography reveals an abnormal location of male genital organs. He is advised to consult a surgeon for early intervention to avoid future complications. Orchiopexy is a surgical procedure for the correction of which of the following abnormalities?","explanation":"**Cryptorchidism** refers to the condition where one or both **testes fail to descend** into the scrotum. Instead, they may be located in the inguinal canal or abdomen. **Orchiopexy** is the surgical procedure performed to bring the undescended testes into the scrotum and secure them in place.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nHypospadias is a congenital condition where the opening of the urethra is on the underside of the penis instead of at the tip. Correction of hypospadias typically involves urethroplasty and penile straightening.\r\n\r\nPhimosis is the inability to retract the foreskin over the glans penis. Circumcision or topical steroids are common treatments for phimosis.\r\n\r\nTorsion refers to the twisting of the testis on its spermatic cord, leading to compromised blood flow. While orchiopexy of the uninvolved testis can be used as a preventive measure against the recurrence of torsion, it does not correct torsion that has already occurred. Detorsion must be performed to restore blood flow in cases of testicular torsion.\r\n\r\nEpispadias is a congenital condition where the urethra opens on the upper surface of the penis. Surgical correction involves epispadias repair, not orchiopexy.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 967.","responses":[{"text":"Torsion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cryptorchidism","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phimosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypospadias","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epispadias","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12958,"text":"A mother of 3 children is admitted for a fourth C-section. She is counseled for a permanent method of contraception. Which of the following are permanent methods of contraception?","explanation":"**Tubal ligation** involves the surgical procedure of ligating or blocking the fallopian tubes, preventing the eggs from reaching the uterus and thus avoiding fertilization. It is a **permanent** method of **contraception** and is intended for individuals who have completed their desired family size and are seeking a long-term and irreversible solution. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nOral pills, subdermal implants, depo-provera injections, and intrauterine contraceptive devices (IUCD), are all temporary or reversible methods of contraception\r\n\r\nOral pills that involve taking hormonal pills daily. They do not provide permanent contraception.\r\n\r\nThe subdermal implant is a small rod inserted under the skin that releases hormones to prevent pregnancy for several years.\r\n\r\nThe Depo-Provera injection must be administered regularly for ongoing effectiveness.\r\n\r\nIUCD involves the insertion of a device into the uterus which remains effective for several years.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Reproductive Module. Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Family Planning, Sub-topic: Clinical Methods of Contraception in Female (IUCD), Surgical Methods.","responses":[{"text":"IUCD","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Depo-Provera injection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subdermal implant","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubal ligation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oral pills","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12959,"text":"A 15-year-old boy is brought to the psychiatry outpatient department by his parents. He reports feeling depressed since childhood and attempted to harm himself by cutting his wrists 1 month ago. He is very distressed as he has always felt like he is a girl trapped in a male body. Recently he started having thoughts of getting surgery to get his genitals changed to that of a female, which in his opinion might help him feel happy and normal. Which of the following terms best describes this disorder?","explanation":"**Gender dysphoria** refers to the distress that may accompany the **incongruence** between one's **experienced gender and their assigned gender** at birth. Individuals with gender dysphoria often experience significant discomfort or distress related to their gender identity, leading to emotional and psychological challenges. The distress in this case is related to the perceived incongruence between the individual's experienced gender (feeling like a girl) and their assigned gender at birth (male).\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThis term typically refers to actions related to sexual activity, and it does not encompass the broader issues of gender identity and dysphoria.\r\n\r\nSexual orientation refers to an individual's emotional, romantic, or sexual attraction to people of the opposite or same sex. It is distinct from gender dysphoria.\r\n\r\nSexual identity relates to how individuals perceive their own sexuality, including factors such as sexual orientation. It is not the most appropriate term for the described distress related to gender identity.\r\n\r\nWhile related, gender identity alone does not capture the distress or discomfort associated with incongruence. Gender dysphoria is a more specific term when referring to distress related to the incongruence between assigned gender and experienced gender.","reference":"G G, G E, R M. Gender dysphoria. PubMed. Published January 2022. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30335346/","responses":[{"text":"Sexual behavior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gender dysphoria","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sexual orientation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sexual identity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gender identity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12960,"text":"An 18-year-old female, married for 5 months presents to you in the clinic, accompanied by her husband, with complaints of non-consummation of marriage due to fear of the sexual act and intense pain whenever the couple attempts intercourse. She previously consulted a gynecologist who prescribed multivitamins and informed her that she had no gynecological problem. You diagnose her with vaginismus as a result of fear associated with intercourse. What is the best management plan in this case?","explanation":"**Vaginismus** is a condition characterized by involuntary contraction of the pelvic floor muscles, making penetration painful or impossible. In many cases, it is associated with psychological factors such as fear, anxiety, or past traumatic experiences.\r\n\r\n**Addressing psychosocial correlates** to tackle the fear of intercourse and providing **informational care** is the best possible option in case of the absence of a gynecological problem. In some cases, cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) or sex therapy may be recommended.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile benzodiazepines may help with anxiety, they are not the primary treatment for vaginismus. Addressing the root psychological causes is essential.\r\n\r\nCounseling the couple by telling them there is no major problem and to keep trying does not address the underlying psychological factors contributing to vaginismus and may increase the patient's distress.\r\n\r\nPrescribing painkillers to be taken before intercourse may provide temporary relief, but they do not address the root cause of vaginismus and may mask important symptoms.\r\n\r\nPrescribing a placebo does not address the psychological and physical aspects of vaginismus and is not an ethical or effective intervention.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Reproductive Module. Subject: Behavioural Sciences, Topic: Evaluate The Local Scenario of Reproductive Health, Sub-topic: Barriers to Access The Health Care Services, How to Achieve RH.","responses":[{"text":"Prescribe short-acting benzodiazepine to be taken prior to intercourse","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Address psychosocial correlates and provide informational care","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prescribe painkillers to be taken prior to intercourse","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prescribe a placebo to be taken prior to intercourse","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Counsel the couple that there is no major problem and to keep trying","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12962,"text":"The organ that shows hyper-echoic fluid-filled areas in polycystic ovarian syndrome is lined by which of the following epithelium?","explanation":"The **ovaries** are lined by the germinal epithelium, which is a **simple cuboidal epithelium**. This type of epithelium is well-suited for the secretory and absorptive functions associated with the developing ovarian follicles.\r\n\r\nIn polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), the ovaries develop small, fluid-filled cysts. These cysts are seen as hyper-echoic fluid-filled areas on imaging studies such as ultrasound.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nSimple squamous epithelium typically lines structures involved in diffusion, such as the alveoli of the lungs or the glomeruli of the kidneys.\r\n\r\nStratified squamous epithelium is typically found in tissues subjected to mechanical stress such as the epidermis of the skin or the lining of the esophagus.\r\n\r\nStratified columnar epithelium is typically found in the digestive tract.\r\n\r\nStratified cuboidal epithelium lines the ducts of sweat glands while ovarian follicles are typically by a single layer of cuboidal cells.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 231.","responses":[{"text":"Stratified squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple cuboidal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple squamous","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12963,"text":"Which of the following is the lymphatic drainage of the ovaries?","explanation":"The **para-aortic lymph nodes** are located along the abdominal aorta bilaterally. They receive lymphatic drainage from the pelvic organs. This group of lymph nodes provides the primary **drainage** pathway for the **ovaries**.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe internal iliac lymph nodes receive drainage from the bladder, rectum, and reproductive organs, but they are not the primary nodes for the ovaries.\r\n\r\nSuperficial inguinal nodes primarily drain the lower extremities and the superficial regions of the abdomen, not the ovaries.\r\n\r\nThe common iliac nodes receive drainage from both the internal and external iliac nodes, forming a larger chain. They are not the primary drainage pathway for the ovaries.\r\n\r\nThe external iliac nodes, along with the internal iliac nodes, contribute to the iliac lymphatic chain, which receives drainage from pelvic structures. However, they are not the primary nodes of the ovaries.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 495-496.","responses":[{"text":"External iliac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Common iliac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal iliac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superficial inguinal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Para-aortic","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12964,"text":"In a patient with polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), which phase of the menstrual cycle is affected due to the elevated ratio of LH to FSH?","explanation":"In polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS), the elevated ratio of luteinizing hormone (LH) to follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) primarily affects the **ovulatory** and **luteal phases** of the menstrual cycle.\r\n\r\nIn PCOS, the disrupted hormonal balance leads to an elevated LH/FSH ratio, which interferes with normal ovarian function. The increased LH levels contribute to **anovulation** (lack of ovulation) or irregular ovulation. This disturbance in ovulation subsequently affects the luteal phase, leading to **inadequate corpus luteum formation** and decreased progesterone production.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe proliferative phase involves the growth of the endometrium, and the menstrual phase involves shedding the uterine lining. These phases are more influenced by estrogen levels and are less directly impacted by the LH/FSH ratio.\r\n\r\nWhile both the luteal and menstrual phases are affected in PCOS, the primary disruption is in the ovulatory phase, leading to irregularities in the subsequent luteal phase and menstrual cycle.\r\n\r\nWhile irregular menstrual flow and disturbances in the follicular phase can occur in PCOS, the primary impact is on ovulation and the subsequent luteal phase.","reference":"Saadia Z. Follicle stimulating hormone (Lh: fsh) ratio in polycystic ovary syndrome (Pcos) - obese vs. Non- obese women. Medical Archives. Published August 2020. Accessed December 9, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7520057/","responses":[{"text":"Luteal and menstrual phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Proliferative and ovulatory phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovulatory and luteal phase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Proliferative and menstrual phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Menstrual flow and follicular phase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12966,"text":"Seminiferous tubules comprise which of the following epithelium?","explanation":"The epithelial lining of the **seminiferous tubules** is often described as a **modified stratified cuboidal epithelium** due to its unique structure supporting spermatogenesis.\r\nIt consists of several layers of spermatogenic **germ cells**. These germ cells are supported by tall, columnar Sertoli cells interspersed throughout the spermatogenic epithelium.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nStratified columnar epithelium lines the vas deferens.\r\n\r\nPseudostratified columnar epithelium lines the epididymis.\r\n\r\nStratified squamous epithelium is found in areas subjected to mechanical stress, such as the skin.\r\n\r\nSimple cuboidal epithelium is found in certain glandular structures such as the ducts of the salivary glands.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 219.","responses":[{"text":"Modified stratified cuboidal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudostratified ciliated","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16078,"text":"Which of the following is the lining epithelium of vas deferens?","explanation":"The **vas deferens** is a muscular tube that carries sperm from the epididymis to the urethra. It is lined by **pseudostratified columnar epithelium**. This type of epithelium appears stratified but consists of a single layer of cells with nuclei at different levels, giving the appearance of multiple layers.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nTransitional epithelium is typically found in organs that undergo stretching, such as the urinary bladder.\r\n\r\nSimple cuboidal epithelium is composed of a single layer of cube-shaped cells and is typically involved in secretion and absorption. It forms the ducts of certain glands such as the salivary glands.\r\n\r\nSimple squamous epithelium is a thin, single layer of flattened cells. It is found in areas where thin and permeable barriers are necessary, facilitating diffusion and filtration. Examples include the lining of blood vessels (endothelium) and alveoli.\r\n\r\nStratified squamous epithelium is often found in areas subject to mechanical stress, such as the skin and the lining of the oral cavity.","reference":"Mescher, Anthony L., and Luiz Carlos Uchôa Junqueira. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill, 2021: 439.","responses":[{"text":"Simple squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudostratified columnar","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transitional epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":16079,"text":"A specimen slide from the external male genital tract is sent for examination. The specimen appears to have pseudostratified columnar epithelium and stereocilia. Which part of the male genital tract is the slide from?","explanation":"The specimen slide is most likely from the **epididymis**; a highly coiled tubular structure located on the posterior aspect of the testis. It serves as a site for the maturation and storage of sperm and is lined by **pseudostratified columnar epithelium**.\r\n\r\nStereocilia are non-motile projections found on the apical surface of the epithelial cells in the epididymis. Stereocilia increase the surface area for absorption and secretion in the epididymis.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe rete testis is a network of tubules located at the hilum of the testis. It is lined by a simple cuboidal epithelium that lacks stereocilia. Instead, the apical surface of each of these cells is covered by microvilli and a cilium.\r\n\r\nThe testis is primarily composed of seminiferous tubules, which are the sites of spermatogenesis. These tubules are lined by spermatogenic epithelium composed of tall columnar Sertoli cells and germ cells.\r\n\r\nThe efferent ductules connect the rete testis to the epididymis. While they share some characteristics with the epididymis, they lack stereocilia.","reference":"Mescher, Anthony L., and Luiz Carlos Uchôa Junqueira. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill, 2021: 439.","responses":[{"text":"Rete testis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seminiferous tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Efferent ductules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epididymis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Testis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20591,"text":"What is the most common cause of abnormal uterine bleeding in adolescents?","explanation":"The most common cause of abnormal uterine bleeding in **adolescents** are **anovulatory cycles**.\r\n\r\nAnovulatory cycles occur when ovulation does not take place, leading to irregular shedding of the endometrial lining, resulting in **abnormal uterine bleeding**. This is a common phenomenon during the initial years after menarche when the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis is still maturing.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile hypothalamic causes can contribute to menstrual irregularities, anovulatory cycles are more prevalent in adolescents due to the immaturity of the hormonal axis.\r\n\r\nUterine polyps can cause abnormal bleeding, but they are not the most common cause in adolescents.\r\n\r\nCarcinoma is an uncommon cause of abnormal uterine bleeding in adolescents. It is more common in older age groups.\r\n\r\nAbortion refers to the termination of pregnancy, and while it can cause bleeding, it is not the most common cause of abnormal uterine bleeding in adolescents.","reference":"Dow Lecture Slides. Reproductive-I Module, Subject: Pathology; Topic: Dysfunctional Uterine Bleeding and Endometrial Hyperplasia; Sub-topic: Dysfunctional Uterine Bleeding.","responses":[{"text":"Anovulatory cycle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamic cause","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Abortion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyp","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20592,"text":"A serous sample of a woman with a regular 28-day cycle shows a peak of 17-β-estradiol over the past 12 hours. However, there is no progesterone. What is most likely to occur within the next three days?","explanation":"In a woman with a regular 28-day cycle, a peak in 17-β-estradiol without a subsequent rise in progesterone suggests that she is likely **approaching ovulation.**\r\n\r\nDuring the ovarian cycle, the rise in 17β-estradiol is associated with the follicular phase, which is characterized by the maturation of ovarian follicles. The **peak in 17β-estradiol** typically precedes ovulation. This peak is usually followed by a surge in luteinizing hormone (LH), triggering ovulation.\r\n\r\nThe **absence of progesterone** suggests that ovulation has not yet occurred. Ovulation is expected to happen within the next few days, leading to the formation of the corpus luteum, which produces progesterone during the luteal phase of the ovarian cycle.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nAfter ovulation, the released egg travels down the fallopian tube and may be fertilized by sperm. If fertilization occurs, the resulting embryo undergoes several divisions and forms a blastocyst, with implantation typically occurring 6 to 12 days after fertilization.\r\n\r\nA decrease in body temperature is associated with the luteal phase, following ovulation. In the scenario described, the woman is likely approaching ovulation rather than the luteal phase.\r\n\r\nMenstruation typically occurs around 14 days after ovulation if fertilization does not take place. In this case, ovulation has not yet occurred, so cessation of menstruation is not expected within the next three days.\r\n\r\nThe onset of menstruation usually occurs around 14 days after ovulation. In this case, since ovulation has not yet occurred, the onset of menstruation is not expected within the next three days.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1029.","responses":[{"text":"Implantation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ovulation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Cessation of menstruation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decrease in body temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Onset of menstruation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":20593,"text":"The secretory phase of menstruation is important for implantation. It is induced by which of the following hormones?","explanation":"The **secretory phase** of the menstrual cycle is induced by both **estrogen** and **progesterone**, which are produced by the corpus luteum after ovulation. These hormones promote the growth of the endometrium and lead to an increase in its vascularity, which is essential for preparing the uterine endometrium for the potential implantation of a fertilized egg. \r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nWhile luteinizing hormone (LH) is essential for triggering ovulation, it is not the primary hormone responsible for the secretory phase. After ovulation, LH levels decline.\r\n\r\nEstrogen does play a role in the secretory phase, but both estrogen and progesterone are needed for the optimal preparation of the endometrium.\r\n\r\nGonadotropins including LH and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) are involved in regulating the menstrual cycle, but they are not the direct inducers of the secretory phase. The secretory phase is more specifically influenced by the hormones produced by the corpus luteum.\r\n\r\nProlactin is involved in the regulation of lactation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1037.","responses":[{"text":"LH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen and progesterone both","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonadotropins","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

